04694nam a22005295i 9780774852302DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071999xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748523027 a10.59962/97807748523022doi  a(DE-B1597)662219  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHT178.C552 ǂb P453 1999eb 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a307.3/416/09511561 aWu, Liangyong, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRehabilitating the Old City of Beijing :bA Project in the Ju'er Hutong Neighbourhood /cLiangyong Wu. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b50 colour illustrations, 30 b&w photos, 10 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aUrbanization in Asia00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe City of Beijing in Historical Perspective -- tPlanning and Development in Beijing since 1949 -- tResidential Development and the Renewal of Derelict Houses -- tOrganic Renewal in Historic Cities -- tTraditional Courtyard Houses and a New Prototype -- tPlanning and Design of the Ju’er Hutong Project -- tPost-Occupancy Evaluation and Lessons from the Planning and Design Experience -- tThe Continuing Debate over Redevelopment -- tFuture Prospects -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1 -- tAppendix 2 -- tAppendix 3 -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Chinese Terms -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSeventy years of revolution and turmoil have had a severe impact on the miraculous ancient urban form of Beijing, but economic growth since the early 1990s has threatened to deal the coup de grace. In Rehabilitating the Old City of Beijing, Wu Liangyong presents an impassioned plea to turn the tide of demolition and offers a new direction for the planning and development of China's capital. Wu, a student and colleague of China's first architectural historian, Liang Sicheng, is a champion of the human-scaled development and a voice for conservation. But above all, he is an architect, and it is through his own projects, built and unbuilt, that he advocates a more humane vision of the city. Wu's project for the renewal of the Ju'er Hutong (Chrysanthemum Lane) neighbourhood in the heart of Beijing's Old City takes pride of place in this book. A thoughtful analysis of those aspects of the ancient capital's features, which the project aims to respect and conserve, is followed by a detailed account of the design and development process of the project itself. Architectural drawings and photographs of the completed project, and data on the neighbourhood's resident population present the state of the art in Chinese residential design and planning -- a field that is deeply challenged by reforms sweeping through the entire economy and society of the country. Urban historians, conservationists, planners, and architectural scholars and practitioners interested in Chinese cities, or in any of the world's great capitals, will want to read this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485230240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774852302423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774852302/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-20